{
  "text": "Post-cardiac surgery, patients tend to experience a downward drift in Hb and anaemia which often leads to a need for blood transfusion [CITATION_1] . In this trial, we also observed a decline in Hb concentration from baseline to week 4 in both treatment groups; however, this decline was significantly less in the iron isomaltoside 1000-treated group compared to the placebo group. The proportion of anaemic patients was significantly lower in the iron isomaltoside 1000 group compared to the placebo group at week 4 (92% of the placebo group patients were anaemic vs. 61\u00c15% in the iron isomaltoside 1000 group). In the study by Garrido-Martin and colleagues, they concluded that the use of IV or oral iron supplementation proved ineffective in correcting anaemia after cardiopulmonary bypass and did not reduce blood transfusion requirements [13] . One possible reason for this finding is that the patient might have received a lower dose of IV iron compared to our study. The patients received 3 doses of 100 mg IV iron (III)-hydroxide sucrose complex per 24 h during pre-and postoperative hospitalization (the cumulative doses are not mentioned), whereas the patients in our study received 1000 mg IV iron isomaltoside 1000.",
